## Afghan Americans

For [Pashtuns](/Pashtuns) in the United States, see [Pashtun Americans](/Pashtun_Americans).

### Ethnic group

**Afghan Americans** ([Dari](/Dari_language): آمریکایی‌های افغان‌تبار *Amrikāyi-hāye Afghān tabar*; [Pashto](/Pashto_language): د امريکا افغانان *Da Amrīka Afghanan*) are [Americans](/Americans) with [ancestry](/Ancestry) from [Afghanistan](/Afghanistan). They represent the largest [Afghan community](/Afghan_diaspora) in [North America](/North_America), with the [Afghan Canadian](/Afghan_Canadians) community holding the second position. Afghan Americans can trace their heritage to any of the diverse [ethnic groups of Afghanistan](/Ethnic_groups_in_Afghanistan).

The presence of an Afghan community in the [United States](/United_States) remained relatively small until the [Soviet invasion of Afghanistan](/Soviet%E2%80%93Afghan_War) in December 1979, which led to a significant influx of [refugees](/Afghan_refugees). Subsequent conflicts and instability in Afghanistan, particularly the more recent [war in Afghanistan](/War_in_Afghanistan_(2001%E2%80%932021)), continued to drive immigration. Afghan Americans are now established across the nation, contributing to the diverse tapestry of American society. Historically, [California](/California), [Virginia](/Virginia), and [New York](/New_York_(state)) have been primary destinations for Afghan immigrants. However, significant populations have also emerged in [Arizona](/Arizona), [Texas](/Texas), [Georgia (U.S. state)](/Georgia_(U.S._state)), [Colorado](/Colorado), [Washington (state)](/Washington_(state)), [Oklahoma](/Oklahoma), [Nebraska](/Nebraska), [Missouri](/Missouri), [North Carolina](/North_Carolina), [Maryland](/Maryland), and [Illinois](/Illinois), illustrating the widespread settlement of this community.

### History and population

The history of Afghan immigration to the United States stretches back further than commonly assumed, with arrivals noted as early as the 1860s. This period coincided with the nascent stages of [Afghanistan–United States relations](/Afghanistan%E2%80%93United_States_relations). Intriguingly, [Wallace Fard Muhammad](/Wallace_Fard_Muhammad), the founder of the Nation of Islam, claimed to be of Afghan origin. A World War I draft registration card from 1917 for an individual named Wallie Dodd Fard listed his birthplace as [Shinka](/Shinkay_District), Afghanistan, and indicated he was residing in [Los Angeles](/Los_Angeles), California, as an unmarried restaurant owner.

Between the 1920s and the 1940s, the number of Afghan immigrants grew into the hundreds. Further immigration occurred between 1953 and the early 1970s, with at least 230 individuals entering the United States through legal channels. Some of these early immigrants were students who benefited from [scholarships](/Scholarship) to pursue higher education at [American universities](/Lists_of_American_universities_and_colleges), laying a groundwork for future intellectual and professional contributions.

#### Afghan refugees and the Refugee Act of 1980

*   Further information: [Afghan refugees](/Afghan_refugees) and [Refugee Act of 1980](/Refugee_Act_of_1980)

Individuals admitted to the United States as [Afghan refugees](/Afghan_refugees) are statutorily recognized as [lawful permanent residents](/Green_card), granting them [green card](/Green_card) status from the date of their arrival. This legislative framework has been crucial in their integration into American society.

The [Soviet invasion of Afghanistan](/Soviet%E2%80%93Afghan_War) in 1979 triggered a massive displacement, forcing approximately five million [Afghans](/Afghans) to seek refuge in other countries. Many found temporary shelter in neighboring [Pakistan](/Afghans_in_Pakistan) and [Iran](/Afghans_in_Iran). From these initial havens, thousands eventually journeyed to [Europe](/Europe), [North America](/North_America), [Oceania](/Oceania), and other parts of the world, forming the nascent [Afghan diaspora](/Afghan_diaspora). It's important to note that individuals born in [Pakistan](/Pakistan), [Iran](/Iran), or [India](/Afghans_in_India) are not, by virtue of their birth location, considered [Pakistanis](/Pakistanis), [Iranians](/Demographics_of_Iran), or [Indians](/Indian_nationality_law). Their official documents, such as birth certificates, unequivocally identify them as [citizens of Afghanistan](/Afghan_identity_card).

The year 1980 marked a significant turning point, as Afghan families began arriving in the United States as refugees or [asylum seekers](/Asylum_seekers). The [Refugee Act of 1980](/Refugee_Act_of_1980) provided a crucial legal pathway for these individuals. In some tragic instances, only one parent was able to make the journey, due to the loss of the other. These families began to establish roots in various regions, most notably the [New York metropolitan area](/New_York_metropolitan_area), [California](/California) (particularly the [San Francisco Bay Area](/San_Francisco_Bay_Area) and the [Los Angeles](/Los_Angeles)-[Orange County](/Orange_County,_California) area), and other parts of the country where established [Muslim community centers](/Islam_in_the_United_States) provided a sense of community and support. [Fremont, California](/Fremont,_California), has emerged as a major hub for Afghan Americans, followed by [Northern Virginia](/Northern_Virginia) and [Queens](/Queens) in [New York City](/New_York_City). Smaller, yet significant, Afghan American communities can also be found in [Texas](/Texas), [Arizona](/Arizona), [Oklahoma](/Oklahoma), [Washington (state)](/Washington_(state)), [Georgia (U.S. state)](/Georgia_(U.S._state)), [Michigan](/Michigan), [Idaho](/Idaho), [Missouri](/Missouri), [Illinois](/Illinois), [Pennsylvania](/Pennsylvania), [Florida](/Florida), [North Carolina](/North_Carolina), [Massachusetts](/Massachusetts), [Maryland](/Maryland), [Connecticut](/Connecticut), [Colorado](/Colorado), [Ohio](/Ohio), [Utah](/Utah), [New Mexico](/New_Mexico), [Oregon](/Oregon), and [Tennessee](/Tennessee). In [Chicago](/Chicago), the 2000 census recorded 556 Afghan Americans, with roughly half residing within the city limits.

The initial wave of Afghan families arriving in the early 1980s primarily consisted of individuals from the wealthier, educated, and [urban](/Urban_area) [elite](/Elite) class. Many had successfully applied for refugee status while residing temporarily in Pakistan and India, and a considerable number had previously lived in [Germany](/Afghans_in_Germany) before undertaking [third-country resettlement](/Third_country_resettlement) in the United States. Subsequent immigration, facilitated by the [family reunification](/Family_reunification) program, brought in communities from more [rural](/Rural_area) areas of Afghanistan. These later arrivals often had less formal education, some being illiterate, and tended to maintain more traditional village lifestyles.

#### Child Citizenship Act of 2000

*   Further information: [Child Citizenship Act of 2000](/Child_Citizenship_Act_of_2000)

Individuals admitted under [8 U.S.C.](/Title_8_of_the_United_States_Code) § 1157 and subsequently granted [green card](/Green_card) status under [8 U.S.C.](/Title_8_of_the_United_States_Code) § 1159(a) possess statutory protections against inadmissibility. This protection remains in effect even if they are not in possession of their green cards, [Afghan passports](/Afghan_passport), [Afghan identity cards](/Afghan_identity_card), or any other form of legal documentation. Furthermore, under the [Child Citizenship Act of 2000](/Child_Citizenship_Act_of_2000), when a [parent](/Parent) becomes [naturalized](/Naturalization) as a U.S. citizen, all of their [children](/Child) automatically become entitled to [naturalization](/Naturalization) through that [American](/Americans) parent. This provision effectively confers [United States nationality](/United_States_nationality_law) upon these children, regardless of whether they were born inside or outside the United States. All such claims to nationality are subject to review by the [federal judiciary of the United States](/Federal_judiciary_of_the_United_States).

The period following the [September 11, 2001 attacks](/September_11_attacks) proved challenging for the Afghan American community, as they faced increased scrutiny and discrimination. President Bush's initiatives aimed at bolstering the economy and integrating immigrants were significantly disrupted by the attacks. This disruption led to a slowdown in the admission of new immigrants between 2001 and 2005. While 406,080 immigrant visas were issued in 2001, this number decreased to 395,005 by 2005, according to data from the Department of Homeland Security.

#### Afghan Allies Protection Act of 2009

*   Further information: [Emergency Afghan Allies Extension Act of 2014](/Emergency_Afghan_Allies_Extension_Act_of_2014)

A U.S. soldier stands with an Afghan American interpreter in [Jalalabad](/Jalalabad), [Nangarhar Province](/Nangarhar_Province), Afghanistan.

In 2001, a news report, lacking specific sources, cited a figure of 200,000 Afghan Americans. This broad estimate may have included individuals from [Afghan Canadian](/Afghan_Canadians) communities. More precise data from the [U.S. Census Bureau](/United_States_Census_Bureau) indicated approximately 65,972 Afghan-Americans in 2006. By 2016, the [American Community Survey](/American_Community_Survey) (ACS) estimated that 94,726 foreign-born Afghan immigrants resided in the United States, reflecting a notable 30% increase over the preceding decade.

Since 2005, a substantial number of Afghans have been admitted to the United States through the [Special Immigrant Visa](/Special_Immigrant_Visa) (SIV) program. This program became particularly vital after the passage of the [Afghan Allies Protection Act of 2009](/Emergency_Afghan_Allies_Extension_Act_of_2014), which was subsequently extended in 2014. The act made Afghans who had risked their lives assisting the [US-led war in Afghanistan](/War_in_Afghanistan_(2001%E2%80%93present)) eligible for SIVs. This initiative established a formal legal pathway for these individuals and their immediate family members to attain [U.S. citizenship](/Citizenship_of_the_United_States).

#### Evacuations of 2021

*   Further information: [Fall of Kabul (2021)](/Fall_of_Kabul_(2021)) and [2021 Kabul Airlift](/2021_Kabul_Airlift)

The [Taliban](/Taliban) resurgence and takeover of Kabul in August 2021 prompted a significant wave of Afghans to seek refuge in the United States, including many who had collaborated with U.S. forces. Official records from the Department of Health and Human Services' Office of Refugee Resettlement indicate that over 100,000 Afghan nationals have arrived in the U.S. since August 2021, with more than 1,600 unaccompanied children among them. Concerns remain for the estimated 150,000 Afghans who aided the United States and were unable to evacuate, including those who worked closely with U.S. military personnel.

#### Discrimination of Refugees

Afghan refugees navigating the complexities of resettlement can face significant challenges, including discrimination, which can exacerbate existing trauma. The ongoing instability in Afghanistan continues to force individuals to flee, and many struggle to find safe refuge. A recent example of this precarious situation is Canada's closure of its Special Immigration Measures Program on July 15, leaving Afghans who relied on it, particularly former employees of the Canadian Armed Forces and government, vulnerable to death or persecution.

### Culture

*   Further information: [Culture of Afghanistan](/Culture_of_Afghanistan)

![Qabuli Palau](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/78/Qabili_Palau.jpg/220px-Qabili_Palau.jpg)
*Qabuli Palau*, a traditional rice dish topped with sweet carrots, raisins, and sliced almonds, often served with lamb, beef, or chicken.

![Aushak](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6b/Aushak_-_Afghan_dumplings.jpg/220px-Aushak_-_Afghan_dumplings.jpg)
Traditional dish [aushak](/Aushak) served at an Afghan restaurant in California.

Like many immigrant groups in the United States, Afghan Americans have progressively integrated into the [American way](/American_way) of life. However, a strong connection to [Afghan culture](/Afghan_culture) persists among those born in Afghanistan. This connection is often expressed through the continued appreciation and practice of Afghan traditions, such as wearing traditional clothing at home, enjoying [Afghan music](/Music_of_Afghanistan) and [Afghan shows](/Television_in_Afghanistan), and savoring [Afghan cuisine](/Afghan_cuisine). Engagement with [Afghan politics](/Politics_of_Afghanistan) also remains a significant aspect for many. The rich oral tradition of storytelling is highly valued, with tales often featuring figures like [Mullah](/Mullah) [Nasreddin](/Nasreddin), and narratives drawn from [Afghan history](/History_of_Afghanistan), myths, and religious lore.

Afghan Americans observe August 19 as [Afghan Independence Day](/Afghan_Independence_Day), commemorating Afghanistan's full independence achieved in August 1919 following the signing of the [Anglo-Afghan Treaty](/Anglo-Afghan_Treaty_of_1919). Small [festivals](/Festival) are often organized in cities with substantial Afghan populations, typically held in parks where the black, red, and green colors of the [Afghan flag](/Flag_of_Afghanistan) are prominently displayed on vehicles. Major religious festivals such as Eid and Nowruz are also widely celebrated. The 2021 American sitcom [United States of Al](/United_States_of_Al) explored the intersection of American and Afghan cultures.

A 2001 [The Washington Post](/The_Washington_Post) article described the Afghan-American community, particularly those concentrated in [Fremont, California](/Fremont,_California) and [Hayward, California](/Hayward,_California), as a "microcosm of the country that's nearly a dozen time zones away." Members of the community acknowledged that while divisions and conflicts present in Afghanistan sometimes carried over to the United States, a shared love for their homeland united them.

#### Ethnicity and race

*   Further information: [Ethnic groups in Afghanistan](/Ethnic_groups_in_Afghanistan) and [religion in Afghanistan](/Religion_in_Afghanistan)

The Afghan American population is comprised of the same diverse [ethnic groups](/Ethnic_groups_in_Afghanistan) found in Afghanistan, including [Pashtuns](/Pashtuns), [Tajiks](/Tajiks), [Hazaras](/Hazaras), [Uzbeks](/Uzbeks), [Turkmen](/Turkmens), [Baloch](/Baloch_people), and numerous others. Since 1945, Afghan Americans have been officially classified as [Caucasians](/Caucasian_race). For [U.S. Census](/United_States_census) purposes, Afghans are categorized racially as either White or Asian Americans. More recently, the proposal for a new census category, SWANA (Southwest Asian and North African), has gained traction as a means to achieve more accurate demographic categorization for groups like Afghan Americans.

#### Religion

*   The [Hazrati Abu Bakr Siddique](/Hazrati_Abu_Bakr_Siddique) [Mosque](/Mosque) in [Flushing, Queens](/Flushing,_Queens), [New York City](/New_York_City).

The majority of Afghan Americans are adherents of [Islam](/Islam), predominantly [Sunni Islam](/Islam_in_Afghanistan), with a significant minority practicing [Shia Islam](/Shia_Islam_in_Afghanistan). Many Afghan Americans in [Northern Virginia](/Northern_Virginia) are affiliated with the [All Dulles Area Muslim Society](/All_Dulles_Area_Muslim_Society), which operates several local branches. Following the [September 11 attacks](/September_11_attacks) in 2001, an Afghan American-run mosque in New York City organized blood drives, held a vigil for the victims of the [World Trade Center](/World_Trade_Center_(1973%E2%80%932001)) (WTC) attacks, and contributed to a memorial fund for the [New York City fire fighters](/New_York_City_Fire_Department).

A community of [Afghan Jews](/History_of_the_Jews_in_Afghanistan) resides in [New York City](/New_York_City), estimated to comprise about 200 families in 2007. Additionally, a group of Afghan Americans in the Los Angeles area identifies with [Christianity](/Christianity_in_Afghanistan). Hussain Andaryas, an Afghan Christian televangelist, belongs to the Hazara ethnic group. Beyond the Abrahamic faiths, communities of [Afghan Hindus](/Hinduism_in_Afghanistan) and [Afghan Sikhs](/Sikhism_in_Afghanistan) also exist, primarily concentrated in the states of [New York](/New_York_(state)) and [Maryland](/Maryland).

#### Media

Afghan Americans have established media outlets to serve their diaspora. These include television channels such as [Ariana Afghanistan](/Ariana_Afghanistan), [Payam-e-Afghan](/Payam-e-Afghan), Tuti TV, and Pamir TV. During the 1990s, Afghanistan TV was broadcast on [KSCI](/KSCI) Channel 18 in Los Angeles, alongside publications like the Afghanistan Mirror magazine. Numerous organizations have also been founded to support Afghan youth, promote solidarity, advocate for women's rights, and address other community needs. More recently, a new radio station, Radio Afghan Los Angeles, has been launched. In 2020, Misaq Kazimi initiated "Afghanistan by Afghans," a TV show and podcast dedicated to showcasing the perspectives of Afghan artists, thinkers, and cultural custodians, which is also featured on Zarin TV.

